{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480614"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:47:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:47:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"85"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"85","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/85"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.09,0.02,0.12,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"85"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52349"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"85","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/85"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"85"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37687"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41983"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42964"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52349"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute onset shortness of breath over the past hour. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She has a 40 pack-year history of smoking and drinks about 25 units of alcohol per week. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 150/min, blood pressure 135/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Her chest is clear on auscultation, with no wheeze or crackles. Chest expansion is symmetrical. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia at 150/min.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Myocardial infarction","Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease exacerbation","Pneumothorax","Panic attack","Pulmonary embolism"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute onset dyspnoea, tachycardia, and hypoxia, which are concerning for a serious cardiopulmonary condition. The most likely diagnosis in this scenario is \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E. Several factors support this diagnosis: the acute onset of symptoms, the presence of significant hypoxia (SpO2 90% on room air), marked tachycardia (150/min), and a clear chest on auscultation despite severe symptoms. Sinus tachycardia is the most common ECG finding in pulmonary embolism, present in about 44% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with chest pain, which is not mentioned in this case. While atypical presentations can occur, especially in women and elderly patients, the clear lungs and lack of specific ECG changes make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) exacerbation\u003C/strong\u003E would be a consideration given the patient\u0027s significant smoking history. However, COPD exacerbations usually present with wheeze and/or crackles on auscultation, which are absent in this case. The acute onset and severity of symptoms are also atypical for a COPD exacerbation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E can present with acute dyspnoea and tachycardia. However, a pneumothorax typically causes asymmetrical chest expansion and decreased breath sounds on the affected side, neither of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epanic attack\u003C/strong\u003E can cause tachycardia and a sensation of shortness of breath. However, panic attacks do not typically cause significant hypoxia (SpO2 90%), making this diagnosis less likely in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of acute onset dyspnoea, tachycardia, hypoxia, and a clear chest examination should prompt strong consideration of pulmonary embolism. Further investigations, such as D-dimer testing and CT pulmonary angiography, would be indicated to confirm the diagnosis and guide management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary embolism should be considered in patients presenting with acute onset dyspnoea, tachycardia, and hypoxia, especially when chest examination is clear.","Sinus tachycardia is the most common ECG finding in pulmonary embolism."],"references":["Kosuge M, Kimura K, Ishikawa T, Ebina T, Hibi K, Kusama I, Nakachi T, Endo M, Komura N, Umemura S. Electrocardiographic differentiation between acute pulmonary embolism and acute coronary syndromes on the basis of negative T waves. Am J Cardiol. 2007 Mar 15;99(6):817-21. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17350373/","Burns E. ECG changes in pulmonary embolism In: Life in the fast lane [online]. 2020. Available at: https://litfl.com/ecg-changes-in-pulmonary-embolism/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37687"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"85"}},